text: Hey y'all :wave: , I am wondering when I use GX in combination with for example BigQuery, will the heavy lifting (meaning the executing of expectations) happen on BigQuery itself? Or will the data from BigQuery be loaded to whatever machine is executing `great_expectation` and that machine also does the heavy lifting (meaning the validations and checking the whole dataset for violations on that data)?
reply_text: Hi <@U017PJTGC9W>, thanks for the question! For BigQuery or any SQL-based datasource, GX will connect and run validations by creating temp tables and executing queries on the database/warehouse itself. The data is not loaded onto the machine running GX.

text: Is the validation of expectations executed on scalable backends (e.g. BigQuery, Snowflake) or will GX load the data on one machine and execute it on there?
reply_text: Hi <@U017PJTGC9W>, please check the answer under your other post: <https://greatexpectationstalk.slack.com/archives/CUTCNHN82/p1683213306162179>

text:
In <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/connecting_to_your_data/database/bigquery/|this guide> it is recommended to connect to BigQuery using `RuntimeDataConnector`. However <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/connecting_to_your_data/how_to_choose_between_working_with_a_single_or_multiple_batches_of_data/#1-determine-if-a-single-batch-or-multiple-batches-of-data-will-be-most-beneficial-in-your-future-use-cases|here> are some other listed aspects on when to use multiple batches of data, which I want to do.
TLDR:
Should I always use the `RuntimeDataConnector` in combination with BigQuery? Or are there use cases where the other connectors make more sense?
reply_text: Hey <@U017PJTGC9W>! In this case, the RuntimeDataConnector is used to support passing in a query at runtime; if you aren't passing a query at runtime and instead just utilizing an existing table, no need for a runtime connector.

text:
On using <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/data_asset/|Data Assets>: Do I always need to use them in combination with `BatchRequest`s or is it possible to use a Data Asset definition without further specifying a `BatchRequest`?

I ran into the case where I pretty much can specify everything within my Data Asset (e.g. split by year & month). Why would I need to specify a BatchRequest for that case?
reply_text:
Hey <@U017PJTGC9W>! Thanks for reaching out.

Batch requests identify a specific set of data, which may include multiple assets, or may be a subset of a single asset, depending on configuration.

Your interaction with them depends on your workflow -- utilizing fluent datasources reduces the need to interact with batch requests, but they are still occasionally needed.

When working with block-config datasources, batch requests are generally required to identify that specific sub-or-superset of your data to be utilized .

text:
It looks like 0.15.48 introduced a breaking change. We have this initialization of `RuntimeBatchRequest` that worked for a while. When I initially implemented it, it wouldn't work without me specifying the table name and the schema, hence both table and query are specified. But now it is throwing this exception. <https://github.com/great-expectations/great_expectations/pull/6999/files#diff-7a22918666c4fa1ccc41f8ef4d63d8605866ad98e75cf620eb344c3cc80aebb2R1238-R1242|https://github.com/great-expectations/great_expectations/pull/6999/files#diff-7a22918666c4fa1ccc41f8ef4d63d86[…]8e75cf620eb344c3cc80aebb2R1238-R1242>
```RuntimeBatchRequest(
            datasource_name=MY_DATASOURCE,
            data_connector_name=MY_DATACONNECTOR,
            data_asset_name=table_name,
            runtime_parameters= {"query": <my_query>},
            batch_identifiers=batch_identifiers,
            batch_spec_passthrough = {"table_name": my_table, "schema_name": my_schema},
        ) ```
reply_text: Hey <@U0207EXTGTV>! Thanks for raising this. You shouldn't need to provide `table_name` & `schema_name` here anymore when specifying a runtime query; the query should be enough. We'll be sure update our guidance in this area.

text:
Hello GX community, i saw a few request here about how to use Ydata-profiling with new version of GX, so i wrote article about that, hope will be helpful!
<https://medium.com/provectus-articles/how-to-use-ydata-profiling-with-great-expectations-v3-api-fc6c2d0035cd>

```from ruamel import yaml

import great_expectations as gx
from great_expectations.core.batch import BatchRequest, RuntimeBatchRequest

context = gx.get_context()
context.list_datasources()

# Reading data from my snowflake table
multi_batch_all_years_batch_request: BatchRequest = RuntimeBatchRequest(
    datasource_name="my_datasource",
    data_connector_name="my_connector",
    data_asset_name="default_name",
    runtime_parameters={"query":f"select * from my table"},
    batch_identifiers={"default_identifier_name": "default_identifier"},
)
expectation_suite_name = "my_onboarding_assistant_suite"

expectation_suite = context.add_or_update_expectation_suite(
    expectation_suite_name=expectation_suite_name
)

data_assistant_result = context.assistants.onboarding.run(
    batch_request=multi_batch_all_years_batch_request,
)
context.add_or_update_expectation_suite(expectation_suite=expectation_suite)

data_assistant_result.plot_metrics()```
Hello all, I just started using GX. As a initial step, I started with data assistants to create expectations for my Snowflake data. The data assistant was able to generate some expectations based on the data. When I plotted the Data Assistant's calculated metrics, the graph is only showing 1 Batch as below.

• Am I using the correct Batch Request to get the snowflake data?
• What are the best practices to use the data assistants on the snowflake data?
reply_text:
Hey <@U0241V62TGE>! Thanks for reaching out.

Take a look at this documentation on Multi-batch usage of Data Assistants.

reply_text:
Hey <@U04Q2FS0ZPB>! Thanks for reaching out. If you have followed <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_data_contexts/how_to_instantiate_a_data_context_without_a_yml_file|this workflow>, then no directories or files are being created in your root directory, this is all done in code.

However, if you have a filesystem & command line available, then <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_data_contexts/how_to_configure_a_new_data_context_with_the_cli|this workflow> will create a directory of the structures given in the guide, and will store generated files (for example, expectation suites and validation results) within that directory structure.

reply_text:
Hey <@U050S1NSPV1>! Thanks for reaching out.

You can absolutely pass `query` to `runtime_parameters` in a <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/api/core/batch/runtimebatchrequest_class/|RuntimeBatchRequest> -- I believe your use case should work. That being said, as a general rule GX leans on the side of operating on data at rest, rather than making any alterations to that data during ingestion or validation. If this particular use case doesn't work out of the box, then this step of your workflow will have to be carried out *before* passing your data into GX.

text: I'm pretty sure that existing datasources and assets from version previous to 16.x may need to be manually updated by rebuilding the asset after upgrading. I've been reading through several questions in community support over the past few days and it seems theres a similar chain of questions regarding people following documentation and that documentation not being in line with assets created before the version upgrade. I'm not positive, but I've been having a lot of issues post upgrading. Just a thought could be mistaken.
reply_text:
Hey <@U02GMMPFCBD>! Thanks for raising this. This is exactly correct (and our messaging hasn't been very clear about this)!

Your previous datasources and assets will either need to continue to be used in the the pre-16.x way (following the older version of the docs), *or* be rebuilt under the new version -- mixing & matching will cause errors. We're working on a migration guide to help make this as clear & painless as possible; thank you for calling this out & your patience as we improve our docs throughout GX. :bow:

text:
How can I specify read_timeout and connection_timeout for validation_s3_store
What are the parameters supported in boto3_options?
reply_text: Hi <@U02M2BXRACS>, GX calls the boto3 <https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/reference/core/session.html#boto3.session.Session.client|session.client()> method. We pass in the service_name (typically s3) and all the options you set in the config as kwargs. I expect any of the parameters listed in the boto3 docs would work, with the exception of config, since it expects a boto3.client.Config object, which we aren't creating. config is where the timeout options are defined. Would you be willing to log a GitHub issue to specify your use case and need for these parameters? To my knowledge boto3 will use its <https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/guide/retries.html|default retry behavior> since we aren't specifying one.

text:
Hello team,
I am trying to setup a `S3StoreBackend`  that points to a docker container with Localstack ( local S3)
I have created my data context config as follows:
``` data_context_config = DataContextConfig(
            datasources=datasources,
            store_backend_defaults=S3StoreBackendDefaults(
                default_bucket_name=s3_bucket,
                expectations_store_prefix=f"great_expectations/expectations/{project_name}",
                validations_store_prefix=f"great_expectations/validations/{project_name}",
                data_docs_prefix=f"great_expectations/data_docs/{project_name}",
                checkpoint_store_prefix=f"great_expectations/checkpoints/{project_name}",
                profiler_store_prefix=f"great_expectations/profilers/{project_name}",
                expectations_store_name=f"great_expectations/expectations_S3_store/{project_name}",
                validations_store_name=f"great_expectations/validations_S3_store/{project_name}",
                evaluation_parameter_store_name=f"great_expectations/evaluation_parameter_store/{project_name}",
                checkpoint_store_name=f"great_expectations/checkpoint_S3_store/{project_name}/{dag_name}",
                profiler_store_name=f"great_expectations/profiler_S3_store/{project_name}",
            ),
            plugins_directory=f"{pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent.resolve()}/plugins",
            data_docs_sites={
                "s3_site": {
                    "class_name": "SiteBuilder",
                    "store_backend": {},
                    "site_index_builder": {
                        "class_name": "DefaultSiteIndexBuilder",
                        "show_cta_footer": "true",
                    },
                }
            },
        )```
reply_text:
Hi <@U03HL4LUP71> - since you're using S3 on Localstack with a specific local endpoint for your stores, you'll need to move away from using the S3StoreBackendDefaults and instead define the stores yourself in the config, similar to what you've done for data_docs_sites. Here's an example for <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_metadata_stores/how_to_configure_an_expectation_store_in_amazon_s3#3-update-your-configuration-file-to-include-a-new-store-for-expectations-on-s3|Expectation Stores on S3>. You'll need to do the same for your other stores.

You may also run into issues using a forward slash in S3 bucket names, but I'm not familiar with whether Localstack supports that - AWS <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/bucketnamingrules.html|seems to not>.

text:
Hi team,
Can a profiler(rule-based or DataAssistant) create expectations with mostly parameter, based on the batch request provided?

text:
Hello everyone, I am trying to figure out the most efficient way to run great expectations with pandas dataframes? Currently I've setup a validator to run a list of RuntimeBatchRequests asynchronously using asyncio. Completing this for 1966 Batches running the validator with a single expectation suite with a single expectation takes 3minutes and 15seconds, which seems like quite a long time? Completing the same expectation suite with a Checkpoint takes ~30s longer, which I imagine is from generating the files? Adding another expectation suite with two more expectations pushed the asynchronous checkpoint time to 10minutes.

Async Batch Validator (1 expectation suite: 1 expectation): 3m15s
Async Batch Checkpoint (1 expectation suite: 1 expectation): 3m42s
Async Batch Checkponit (2 expectation suites: 3 expectations): 10m01s

I wonder if there is a way of passing in all the batch requests at one time to the Checkpoint and if this would improve the efficiency? Any help/advice would be much appreciated! :slightly_smiling_face: Thank you!

(Also, I feel like suppressing the "Calculating Metrics: 100%" printout will also improve the completion time but I haven't figured out how to do that? I thought I could do it via changing the logging level to warning but didn't seem to work... :thinking_face:)
reply_text:
Hey <@U04LAN140LA>! Thanks for reaching out.

You can pass a `validations` key to a Checkpoint, specifying a list of `batch_request`s and `expectation_suite_name`s, allowing for multiple validations within a single checkpoint. This looks something like:

```
checkpoint = gx.checkpoint.checkpoint.SimpleCheckpoint(name='test_checkpoint', data_context=context)

checkpoint.run(validations=
               [
                   {'batch_request': batch_request, 'expectation_suite_name': 'test_suite'},
                   {'batch_request': batch_request2, 'expectation_suite_name': 'test_suite2'}
               ]
              )```
Additionally, when working with Pandas, GX is dependent on your local compute & memory; when working with a large number of in-memory dataframes, it is possible that there could be memory/compute issues -- depending on the expectations / operations, there could be a large amount of metadata or slices of your dataframes being persisted at once.

text: Hello Everyone - We have setup the GE at local and made it work for our use-case. We are storing the test result in a database, so we don't want GE to create uncommited/validations/<TEST_SUITE>/_none_/<date folder>/*.*json files and data_docs/* ......Is there a way we can force GE not to create these folder and files.
reply_text:
Hey <@U04NBTVE3TQ>! Thanks for reaching out. In your `great_expectations.yml` config, you should be able to pass `limit_validation_results: 0` to prevent these files from being generated:

```data_docs_sites:

 local_site:

   class_name: SiteBuilder

   show_how_to_buttons: true

   store_backend:

     class_name: TupleFilesystemStoreBackend

     base_directory: uncommitted/data_docs/local_site/

   site_index_builder:

     class_name: DefaultSiteIndexBuilder

     validation_results_limit: 0```

text: Does anyone have any idea about this error ? And how to resolve it ?
reply_text:
I hit similar error. I think you need to try to ensure that pydantic version is 1.10.0 and above.

See they implemented the fix in this version atleast.
<https://github.com/pydantic/pydantic/blob/v1.10.0/pydantic/validators.py|https://github.com/pydantic/pydantic/blob/v1.10.0/pydantic/validators.py>

On the other hands, bumping up Airflow version ia not preferrable as it might break other existing DAGs.

But hopefully this could help you out.

NoSuchKey error usually is due to finding the key that is not in a given location/path

from this part,
```great_expectations.exceptions.exceptions.InvalidKeyError: Unable to retrieve object from TupleS3StoreBackend with the following Key: great-expectations/expectations/great-expectations/expectations_store/expectations_suite_1.json```
the prefixing is redundant, that's why no such key can be found

reply_text:
Hey <@U04QP7CH2D9>! This workflow can be simplified to the idea of:

1. Generating Expectations
2. Applying those Expectations to a second table
While the UCP can accelerate this process, it's not necessary; especially where you're only looking to compare on a few metrics, I think it will be easier for you to build the suite you want in reference to the <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/tutorials/getting_started/tutorial_create_expectations|first table via a standard workflow>, and then apply that suite to the second table as in Step 5 of that guide.

    def _sqlalchemy(cls, dataframe, start_datetime, end_datetime, gap, **kwargs):
        print(dataframe)

        def date_diff_in_months(df):
            col_start = column(start_datetime)
            col_end = column(end_datetime)
            col_gap = column(gap)
            if col_start is None or col_end is None or col_gap is None:
                return None

            # Calculate the difference in months between the start_datetime and end_datetime columns
            diff_months = cast(
                (func.strftime("%Y", col_end) - func.strftime("%Y", col_start)) * 12
                + (func.strftime("%m", col_end) - func.strftime("%m", col_start)),
                Integer,
            )
            return col_gap == diff_months

        return date_diff_in_months(dataframe)```
e.g. func.strftime is not supported by postgress and I would need to use something like EXTRACT(YEAR FROM end_datetime)
Thanks for your hints.
reply_text:
Hey <@U04QPAVL8Q6>! Also interested to see what the community has to say here.

Additionally, you may be interested in <https://github.com/great-expectations/great_expectations/blob/5d936aaa77b0892832e1342fd0f04af7504bb371/contrib/experimental/great_expectations_experimental/expectations/expect_query_to_have_no_duplicate_value_combinations.py|this MultiColumn Query-based Custom Expectation>; doing something like this would allow you to explicitly write a SQL query to power your metric.

text: Hi, GX team - What are the difference between `context.create_expectation_suite()` vs `profiler.build_suit()` and `context.datadoc()` vs `validator.save_expectation_suite()`?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04RJ5CUP2S>!

`context.create_expectation_suite()` creates an empty expectation suite that you can later populate with expectations.

`profiler.build_suite()` executes a profiler against your data to build an expectation suite pre-populated with some basic expectations related to your data.

`context.build_data_docs()` builds your Data Docs (html reports on your data validations) from your previously executed validations.

`validator.save_expectation_suite()` saves the  expectation suite actively being build with your validator, so that you may later pass that suite into a checkpoint for validation.

text:
Hi, GX team - I would like to know how customized GX works. What I want to apply is let’s say that we have specific value range depending on time. For instance, the temperature range value check over the time period.

Suppose that we have date and temperature values in BigQuery. Then, we can set up the specific column to be a specific value such as [min=70, max=120] for the range between June and Sep, and [min=-10, max=50] for the range between Dec and Feb. The base language is Python. I was thinking to use <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/conditional_expectations/|conditional> expectations, but is it required to have only one value? What other options can I use?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04RJ5CUP2S>! Thanks for reaching out. There are some limitations on conditional expectations; you may be able to better address the functionality you're looking for here by utilizing a RuntimeDataConnector & RuntimeBatchRequest. You can pass a `query` to `runtime_parameters` in that batch request, filtering your data asset at that point.

Depending on your use case, it may also be possible to create a <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/expectations/creating_custom_expectations/how_to_create_custom_query_expectations/|Custom Query Expectation> that includes those conditions as a part of the defined query.

Here is the check list that the custom expectation passed:
Completeness checklist for ExpectQueriedCustomQueryToReturnNumRows (BETA):
 :heavy_check_mark: Has a valid library_metadata object

    :heavy_check_mark: “Expect the number of rows returned from custom query to be equal to specified value.”

Hi, I need help accessing Parquet files from an S3 bucket using Fluent Datasource.

Using Fluent Datasource, I am trying to access Parquet files from an S3 bucket, and I am getting the following error, which says two fields are missing. Any help would be greatly appreciated.

*Here is my code:*

`import great_expectations as gx`

`context = gx.get_context()`

`datasource_name = "s3_ds"`
`bucket_name = "some_unique_bucket"`
`boto3_options = {}`

`datasource = context.sources.add_spark_s3(`

`data_asset = datasource.add_parquet_asset(`
	`name="s3_asset",` 
	`batching_regex= "part-(?P<id>\d{4})\.snappy.parquet",`
	`s3_prefix="data/raw_data/",`
`)`

*Error:*

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File “<stdin>“, line 1, in <module>
  File “/Users/sasen/Documents/My Work/data-quality/gx-demo/test/venv/lib/python3.10/site-packages/great_expectations/datasource/fluent/sources.py”, line 305, in _add_asset_factory
    asset = asset_type(name=name, **kwargs)
  File “/Users/sasen/Documents/My Work/data-quality/gx-demo/test/venv/lib/python3.10/site-packages/great_expectations/datasource/fluent/file_path_data_asset.py”, line 105, in __init__
    super().__init__(**data)
  File “pydantic/main.py”, line 341, in pydantic.main.BaseModel.__init__
pydantic.error_wrappers.ValidationError: 2 validation errors for ParquetAsset
datetimeRebaseMode
  field required (type=value_error.missing)
int96RebaseMode
  field required (type=value_error.missing)
reply_text:
Hey <@U04TBGFPS3U>! Thanks for reaching out.

You should be able to pass both `datetimeRebaseMode` & `int96RebaseMode` to `add_parquet_asset(...)`; take a look at <https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-data-sources-parquet.html|this documentation> for more on what these do.

They both take either `"EXCEPTION"`, `"CORRECTED"`, or `"LEGACY"`.

reply_text: Hey <@U04TDCXS3GT>! I believe to do this you'll need to override the inherited `_validate(...)` method when defining your Custom Expectation; this will allow you to return the specific data you are looking for. You may be able to pass this into `unexpected_values` in a ValidationResult object returned from your `_validate(...)` method without having to do any custom rendering; that's what I would try first!

text:
Hi all! I am trying to add a custom field in our Data Doc Validation results that stands for `"Engineer who owns this data (Contact)": "<mailto:engineer@email.com|engineer@email.com>"`. Ideally this value would be found in the Data Docs, so non-technical data users know who to contact if they get a failed validation.

Does anyone know how I could configure thing? Would it be in the Batch Request, Validator, or Checkpoint?

For context I am working with Great Expectation in an AWS Databricks Notebook, and my Data Docs are written and stored in an S3 bucket.
reply_text:
Hey <@U04V7JB8HJS>! Thanks for reaching out.

We would actually look to set this in the Expectation Suite, as the suite represents the guarantee (expectations) for the data.
This can be done by accessing the suite and setting a meta note:

```suite = context.get_expectation_suite("expectation_suite_name")

suite.meta.update({"notes": "<your_note_here">})

context.save_expectation_suite(suite)```
When your docs are next built, that note will be included with that expectation suite.

text:
sqlalchemy.exc.DatabaseError: (pyathena.error.DatabaseError) An error occurred (InvalidRequestException) when calling the StartQueryExecution operation: line 1:8: mismatched input 'TEMPORARY'. Expecting: 'OR', 'SCHEMA', 'TABLE', 'VIEW'
[SQL: CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE "gx_temp_96306502" AS SELECT *
FROM muthu_data
WHERE true]
reply_text:
Hey <@U0533EALVPC>! Thanks for reaching out.

You can pass `create_temp_table` as `False` to your Datasource.

Depending on how your datasource is configured, that may look like:

```datasource = great_expectations.datasource.fluent.SQLDatasource(..., create_temp_table=False)```
or something like:

```datasource_config: dict = {
    "name": "my_datasource_name",
    "class_name": "Datasource",
    "module_name": "great_expectations.datasource",
    "execution_engine": {
        "class_name": "SqlAlchemyExecutionEngine",
        "module_name": "great_expectations.execution_engine",
        "connection_string": CONNECTION_STRING,
        "create_temp_table": False
    },
}```
That should resolve this error.

reply_text:
Hey <@U053A3WD0HJ>! Thanks for reaching out.

Just to clarify, is your `great_expectations.yml` located at:

`/app/prefect-airbyte/great_expectations/great_expectations.yml`

or

`/app/great_expectations/great_expectations.yml` ?

This is the error that surfaces when there is no valid `great_expectations.yml` provided for some reason, e.g. no `great_expectations` directory where this code is being executed, the path to a directory isn't provided or there is no `great_expectations` directory located there, and a key is provided which precludes generating an InMemory context.

In this case, if your `great_expectations` directory is at `/app/prefect-airbyte/great_expectations`, I would try:

```context = gx.get_context(context_root_dir="/app/great_expectations/")```
Specifying `context_root_dir` is important here; pointing directly to the `yml`, or not providing the appropriate argument name, will prevent this from working.

```datasource = context.get_datasource(datasource_name = "existing name")```
or delete the datasource with the existing name and create a new one:

```context.delete_datasource(datasource_name = "existing name")```

Hello everyone, do you have any idea on how to use GX to test data in a rdbms that doesn't support CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE AS SELECT  ?     In my case I'm using tidb, which only supports grammar like :

reply_text:
Hey <@U054HK3K7BL>! Thanks for reaching out.

You can pass `create_temp_table` as `False` to your Datasource.

Depending on how your datasource is configured, that may look like:

```datasource_config: dict = {
    "name": "my_datasource_name",
    "class_name": "Datasource",
    "module_name": "great_expectations.datasource",
    "execution_engine": {
        "class_name": "SqlAlchemyExecutionEngine",
        "module_name": "great_expectations.execution_engine",
        "connection_string": CONNECTION_STRING,
        "create_temp_table": False
    },
}```

text: Hi all! Quick question - how is `data_asset_type` intended to be used?
reply_text:
Hey <@U054QTK2EC9>! Per our API documentation, `data_asset_type` has been deprecated since version `0.14.0`.

If you're using a version that still requires `data_asset_type`, you would specify both the `class_name` & `module_name` of your asset. For example:

```datasources:
  dev_postgres_db:
    class_name: SqlAlchemyDatasource
    data_asset_type:
      class_name: SqlAlchemyDataset
      module_name: great_expectations.dataset```

text:
Hello everyone,

I have a question regarding *custom expectations*. I have created one inside my `plugins_directory` defined as well in the *data context*, however my expectation function remains unknown when I called from a JSON file (`expectation suite`) . It only works when I called it implicitly inside my Python script with an Import. Is it normal ?

Thanks in advance.
reply_text:
Hey <@U055HGUMA01>! This is correct.

Currently, Custom Expectations within the plugins directory are only registered once:

1. Your context has been instantiated, and
2. You have imported the expectation.
If you are, for example, running a script which executes a checkpoint containing a custom expectation, you will still need to import that expectation within that script, to ensure that it is able to be run.

```import great_expectations as gx

context = gx.get_context()

from expectations.your_custom_expectation import ExpectThingToBe```

text:
Hi guys!

*Context*
Currently we have set-up Great Expectations in a Databricks Workspace (using Azure Blob Storage as a backend for the stores) to support us in validating data quality (=expectations) on our data sources. This is done by loading a dataset into a Spark DataFrame (with Spark SQL) inside a notebook and then passing it onto the _SparkExecutionEngine_ in Great Expectations. This SparkExecutionEngine is, however, not supported by the <https://datahubproject.io/docs/metadata-ingestion/integration_docs/great-expectations/|out-of-the-box integration with DataHub>, which only supports a _SqlAlchemyExecutionEngine_.

*Question*
_What is the recommended approach for integrating Great Expectations running on Databricks with DataHub?_

As we currently view it, we have two options:
1. Attempt to rewrite our Great Expectations set-up to work with the SqlAlchemyExecutionEngine (if that's possible with SparkSQL/Databricks).
2. Fork great-expectations and attempt to extend the DataHubValidationAction such that it works in our specific case.
reply_text:
Hi <@U0560FEK46P>! The DataHub integration was built and is maintained by DataHub, so their <https://github.com/datahub-project/datahub/tree/master/metadata-ingestion/src/datahub/integrations/great_expectations|repo> contains the code for the DataHubValidationAction and would be the starting point for an extension. You could also check with their <https://slack.datahubproject.io/|Slack> community to see if anyone has done something similar.

You can also use the SQLAlchemyExecutionEngine to connect to Databricks data. Here's an <https://greatexpectationstalk.slack.com/archives/CUTCNHN82/p1675933871792389?thread_ts=1675334424.191489&cid=CUTCNHN82|example>.

text:
Hi folks, I'm fairly new to GE, so it could be I overlooked something in the docs. I'm trying to implement data quality checks against an MS SQL database. The database is doing a full reload each week. Some of the data quality checks I want to do are with respect to the data from previous week (which is not available anymore) e.g. number of records in the database should be greater than previous week.
How would I go about implementing this using GE?
reply_text: Hi <@U056H3SNP96>, thanks for reaching out :handshake::skin-tone-2: You need to save the number of records week by week, somewhere so that it is available for analysis. You could save the number of records and their date in a database. Then, by querying the database not only for the data but also for the reference number of records, you can set up a workflow (which can be done in several ways) in which you apply an expectation that checks whether the number of records for this week (or other time range) is greater than/less than/equal to the previous week's number of records. Let me know if you need further clarification or an example

text: Hello guys, how are you ? I'm currently starting with GE. I find it super cool and I'm fancying the documentation. However, there's something I'm unsuccessfully trying to grasp: The difference between using a Validator and a Checkpoint. I know they are both used to apply expectations but I'm having a hard time seeing the logic behind. Could you please shed some light on this ? Thank you ever so much in advance.
reply_text:
Hello!
In Great Expectations, Validators and Checkpoints serve different purposes in the data validation workflow:
1. Validators: Validators in GE are used to define expectations on your data and validate it against those expectations. They allow you to define various types of expectations, such as column presence, data type, range, uniqueness, etc. Validators are typically defined as part of an Expectation Suite, which is a collection of related expectations. You can create multiple validators to validate different aspects of your data. Validators help you define the "rules" or expectations that your data should adhere to.
2. Checkpoints: Checkpoints, on the other hand, are used to manage the execution of validations against your data. They provide a way to organize and automate the validation process. A Checkpoint specifies which data to validate, which Validator (or Expectation Suite) to use, and where to store the validation results. Checkpoints allow you to define a specific validation routine for your data, including the data source, expectation suite, and result storage options. You can execute a Checkpoint to run the validation process and store the validation results for analysis and monitoring.
In summary, Validators define the expectations and rules for your data, while Checkpoints provide a way to execute and manage the validation process.

text: Hi everyone! I'm working on a validation that checks if the values of columns are in a set using the `"expect_column_distinct_values_to_be_in_set"` expectation. The set changes occasionally, so I used the `.add_or_update_expectation_suite` method in the data context to update the set when it changes. But instead of updating my expectation, it adds a new one, and now I have multiple replications of this expectation in my json file. Can you help me find a way of updating the set in the expectation without adding the expectation multiple times in my expectation suite json?? Thanks!
reply_text:
Hi <@U05940SJ34G>,instead of updating it manually (which is why it's adding a new thing every time), you can use the validator to update your suite. It will check for the existing expectation for that column and update the kwargs. I have tested this with an existing suite having other expectations on other columns including the same expectation name i.e. `expect_column_distinct_values_to_be_in_set` for other columns and they remain unchanged. This only updates the one you are targetting.

Hope this helps.

text:
Hi everyone, my team is testing GX for our daily data production. I have a question about implementing customized metrics and expectations.
We want to evaluate
1. the correlation and mean absolute error between two columns, so ideally something like `expect_column_pair_values_correlation_to_be_between`and;
2. the percentage change/difference between the means/medians of two columns, so ideally something like `expect_column_pair_means_difference_to_be_between`.
However we are not sure if we shall use `ColumnAggregateMetricProvider` or `ColumnPairMapMetricProvider` , or we have to create metric provider and expectation family by ourselves.
Another simple way is to add new columns like columnA * columnB and use `column_mean` to get the correlation. But we want to avoid these cumbersome steps if possible.
reply_text: Hello, <@U05B3B3EQ9Y> — it looks like you are interested in Column-Pair Aggregate metrics; is this correct?  If so, we do not yet have “an easy” way to do it — you would have to follow the pattern used for `great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_kl_divergence_to_be_less_than.py` but implement the logic for two columns in the aggregate sense, such as in the existing single-column aggregate metrics.  It is on our roadmap to develop a ColumnPairAggregateMetricProvide, but I cannot give a timeline at this point.  In short, whenever a metric deals with a statistic over all rows, that would be “Aggregate”.  If the metric compares the value in a given row to some value, then it is “Map”.  If you need the result quickly, I believe that your idea about a new column that reflects the information from ColumnA and ColumnB combined — and use the ColumnMean metric/expectation then it is a very good approach.  I highly recommend that you explore it.  I hope that this helps a little bit.  Thank you very much, and thank you for using GX!

```validator = context.get_validator(batch_request = your_batch_request, context = your_context)

text:
Hi all, hi <@U049GNPB79A> (I saw you developed that feature for BigQuery)
I want to use GX with BigQuery and create temp tables in a specified dataset but when creating a batch request I cannot provide the `temp_table_schema_name` parameter. `table_asset.batch_request_options` also comes back empty and I'm wondering what's wrong with my setup. Here's the complete code I'm using:
```import great_expectations as gx
context = gx.get_context()

connection_string = !!!REDACTED!!!

datasource = context.sources.add_or_update_sql(
    name="verify_setup", connection_string=connection_string, create_temp_table=True
)

verify_setup_table = !!!REDACTED!!!

if verify_setup_table in datasource.get_asset_names():
    table_asset = datasource.get_asset(verify_setup_table)
else:
    table_asset = datasource.add_table_asset(
        name=verify_setup_table, 
        table_name=!!!REDACTED!!!
    )

# comes back empty
table_asset.batch_request_options

batch_options = {"temp_table_schema_name": "tech_great_expectations_temp_ttl_7d"}
my_batch_request = table_asset.build_batch_request(options = batch_options)```
This results in:
```---------------------------------------------------------------------------
InvalidBatchRequestError                  Traceback (most recent call last)
Cell In[63], line 24
     21 table_asset.batch_request_options
     23 batch_options = {"temp_table_schema_name": "tech_great_expectations_temp_ttl_7d"}
---> 24 my_batch_request = table_asset.build_batch_request(options = batch_options)

File /mnt/encrypted_data/git/gx/venv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/great_expectations/datasource/fluent/sql_datasource.py:706, in _SQLAsset.build_batch_request(self, options, batch_slice)
    704     allowed_keys = set(self.batch_request_options)
    705     actual_keys = set(options.keys())
--> 706     raise gx_exceptions.InvalidBatchRequestError(
    707         "Batch request options should only contain keys from the following set:\n"
    708         f"{allowed_keys}\nbut your specified keys contain\n"
    709         f"{actual_keys.difference(allowed_keys)}\nwhich is not valid.\n"
    710     )
    712 return BatchRequest(
    713     datasource_name=self.datasource.name,
    714     data_asset_name=self.name,
    715     options=options or {},
    716     batch_slice=batch_slice,
    717 )

InvalidBatchRequestError: Batch request options should only contain keys from the following set:
set()
but your specified keys contain
{'temp_table_schema_name'}
which is not valid.```
reply_text:
Hi <@U05CY2PFEET> so firstly, batch requests aren't used to create and filter for temp tables in a specified dataset. It's used to filter specific table, e.g., by a specific column and its value. For Bigquery cases like yours, you would use `add_splitter_*` function to make that happen.

So normally you would use batch requests this way:

```table_asset = datasource.get_asset(verify_setup_table)

table_asset.add_splitter_column_value(column_name = 'column_a')

print(table_asset.batch_request_options)

-> ('column_a')```
And then you use build batch request to specify what value you want to filter on for column_a
```tabale_asset.build_batch_request(options = {'column_a':'value1'})```
In this case, the asset now is further filtered by looking a situation where the column_a has value1.

text: Hi all, does GX profiles the data i.e. give the *data stats* like mode, median, mean, quantiles, etc.. for each column type in a table?
reply_text: Hey <@U0241V62TGE>! GX profiling will set expectations around certain of these; however, it is intended as a tool to validate these metrics, not to deliver specific stats. Depending on your data, GX may or may not set expectations around these.

text: Hi all, does GX profiles the data i.e. give the *data stats* like mode, median, mean, quantiles, etc.. for each column type in a table?
reply_text: For EDA Profiling one recommendation would be ydata-profiling (formerly Pandas-profiling). They previously also had an integration to create expectations for GE but I think this is discontinued

reply_text: Hey <@U028K9LJQR1>! GX supports Spark Dataframes, Pandas Dataframes, and SQLAlchemy datasources.

text: when switching to fluent datasources, how should we reference credentials like for instance, a snowflake private key passhprase and private key path? Are we supposed to set these credentials up in uncommited/config_variables or is this a retired strategy? I am on the latest version of GX and trying to rebuild my snowflake datasources
reply_text: Hi <@U02GMMPFCBD>, we have the Snowflake connection string format defined in our docs for connecting to SQL data fluently. It calls for a username/password, and you can store the password in an environment variable or in config_variables.yml. <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/connecting_to_your_data/fluent/database/how_to_connect_to_sql_data>

text:
After reading docs for a while, I am wondering: how do you remove expectations from a validator or a suite, besides editing the text file?

Rationale: Let’s say I have five csv files from 2015-2020. I load all of them as a batch. Then I create a batch request for the first four years and create an expectation suite using the Data Assistant. After this, I get around 100 expectations. Nice!

Then I validate the last year against the expectations, to check if there are significant changes year over year. I run the validation and discover that around 25 expectations failed. I review the expectations and discover that some of those rules are too strict or would not apply to future batches.

What is the easiest way to remove those expectations?

I assume I would need to save the new ExpectationSuite without the 25 rules under another name but… Is there any simple way to do it?

Somehow I would expect some interactive mode in DataDocs where you could select all, select none or select one by one, then export the subset of Expectations under a new name.
reply_text:
Hey <@U02V8LYNPGU>! Thanks for reaching out.

<https://greatexpectationstalk.slack.com/archives/CUTCNHN82/p1684925527181739|This> as shared by <@U057Q1CSU9K> would be the programmatic approach -- the process you're describing through data docs is one of the planned features for <https://greatexpectations.io/cloud|GX Cloud>.

text:
Hi GX team!
I’m using the DatabaseBackendStores to store expectation suites and checkpoints. Right now, I am only able to store the checkpoint_name/expectation_suite_name and value in the tables. Is there a way for me to add more columns - some that are extracted from the expectation suites + checkpoints files themselves (config_version, batch_request, data_asset_name) and other metadata that is set on insert to the database table (i.e. last date modified, unique id)? Where can I find a list of keys that can be used for the expectation suite and checkpoints DatabaseBackendStores (`keys_column` in the great_expectations config file)?
Thanks in advance!
reply_text: Hey <@U03199HJ7GV>! Thanks for reaching out. GX doesn't currently offer this functionality built-in. Would you be willing to raise this in a Feature Request on GitHub? That will help us to better understand and review this functionality.

text:
Hi everyone,
I'm looking for an expectation that checks wether the values in a column are between x and y *or are null.* 
So basically just like "expect_column_values_to_be_between" but Null values should be also evaluated as correct. Is there an existing Expectation or parameter that does that?
reply_text: Hey <@U037RSBLQCS>, thanks for reaching out :handshake::skin-tone-2::coffee: You can bypass this hurdle by inserting an auxiliary column in your dataset that marks as True (or any other ID you see fit) when it is between x and y or is null. Afterwards, you can apply expect_column_values_to_be_in_set to the auxiliary column and have the result be all-inclusive. Nulls in the expectations in the store are characterized by the fact that Nulls are returned on par with unexpected, but you can use this workaround. I hope it is useful

text: <#CUTCNHN82|gx-community-support> How to setup oracle connectivity with great_expectation
reply_text: Hi <@U03KBFTEJ9K>, we don't have official docs on supporting integration with Oracle. Here's more general docs on connecting with GX and SQL-based datasources: <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/tutorials/getting_started/how_to_use_great_expectations_with_sql>

text:
Hey!
Is there currently a way to set a severity of expectations? For examples, some distributional expectations that I use are quite noisy, but disabling them by setting `threshold: None` removes visibility completely
Is there (or is it possible to add without tons of code) a concept of warnings?
reply_text:
Hey <@U03QJL69GDV>! Thanks for reaching out.

This is not something currently supported by GX; however, this idea is under discussion internally and has previously been captured <https://github.com/great-expectations/great_expectations/issues/4186|here>. Please feel free to comment on that PR if you'd like to see this functionality come to GX!

text: Hi everyone, I'm working on version 0.15.41 and just noticed something odd in the data docs. I'm using a query store as a parameter in an expectation suite to check the row count of a table in a different database and it all runs properly. When viewing the data docs for this validation however, the expectation shows as "Must have exactly None rows". The json validation results do show the expected value (the value of the query from my query store), it's just the data docs do not. Has anyone else experienced this, or know if this was fixed in a newer version?
reply_text:
Hey <@U03S5EM4XB8>! Thanks for reaching out.

We have had some motion in this area in recent weeks; it's possible this is resolved on latest `0.16.15`.

If this isn't resolved by upgrading, please feel free to open an Issue on GitHub detailing this behavior; that will help us to better investigate what may be happening here.

reply_text: Hi <@U03TW0JHZE0> I think you can achieve your goals creating two expectations suites and assigning them to different batch requests. You can even copy some of the expectations from one suite to the other to make it simpler.

text: Is it possible to publish GX result to power BI?
reply_text: Hey <@U0407LPAS2U>! GX doesn't have any official support for exporting to power BI; your validation results typically live as JSON objects within your `great_expectations` directory, and these may be parsed & utilized however you wish -- some users do parse these and send them to BI tools via their own methods.

text:
Hi, I am working with Custom Query Expectations and have many questions regarding them.
• QueryExpectations *must* have the following attributes set:         1. `domain_keys`: a tuple of the *keys* used to determine the domain of the            expectation         2. `success_keys`: a tuple of the *keys* used to determine the success of            the expectation.
reply_text:
Hey <@U0408PXU07R>! Thanks for reaching out. Bear with me; this is going to be a lot of text!

To your first bullet point, that is exactly correct; the metric specified under `metric_dependencies` is utilized to execute your query, the results of which are then made available to your `_validate` method.

To your second bullet, calling `run_diagnostics()` on that expectation will allow you to inspect the results:

```diagnostics = ExpectQueriedColumnValuesToExistInSecondTableColumn().run_diagnostics()

print([x for x in diagnostics["tests"]])
print([x for x in diagnostics["errors"]])```
To your third bullet, when you define `success_keys`,  the items in the tuple are the names of the parameters *which are available for you to use during the evaluation of your Custom Expectation*. Defining `success_keys` is what makes those specific parameters available. Likewise, `domain_keys` are utilized to help define the domain on which your expectation will operate, and specifying those keys makes those parameters available, while allowing for an explicit separation of their function relative to success keys. Take a look at <https://greatexpectations.io/blog/pass-custom-parameters-in-custom-expectations-and-optimize-your-gx-workflows|this blog post> detailing a bit more about these keys, and what can / should be passed here.

We then optionally set default values for these keys, allowing for default customization of your expectation reducing the amount of parameters that *need* to be provided at runtime. In the case of QueryExpectations, explicitly setting a default query here allows the expectation to be utilized with that default query, or *optionally* provide a different query.

By the time we get to the `_validate` method, *all* of our keys have been defined (either by default or at runtime), and are all available via `configuration` for reference within that method. The delineation between success & domain keys is necessary to both to help expectations be self-documenting, and to enable functionality within the actual metric computation running your query.

To your fourth bullet, that doc is correct. When utilizing Custom Expectations, they must be imported after instantiating your Data Context. Many users will create import methods for particular use-cases that can be called within their workflows to minimize overhead on making these imports.

text:
Hello GX team! :wave:

I’ve been studying your documentation to gain a better understanding of the framework, but I’ve found it challenging to comprehend some concepts. This seems to be due to the different ways of achieving the same goal. I also get the impression that most of the time, I’m being directed to take the more complicated route :see_no_evil:.

For instance, when creating an Ephemeral Data Context, the instructions guide me to import two classes, followed by the <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_data_contexts/instantiating_data_contexts/how_to_explicitly_instantiate_an_ephemeral_data_context/|EphemeralDataContext>. Then, I need to run two more commands before I finally have a context that can be converted to a file. :disappointed_relieved:

However, prior to reaching this documentation page, I had completed the <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/tutorials/quickstart/|quickstart tutorial>, where creating an EphemeralDataContext was quite straightforward:
```import great_expectations as gx
context = gx.get_context()```
I’m not trying to complain, just seeking clarity :v:. I want to understand if this is a strategic decision, or if we could begin all the detailed documentation pages, like the Ephemeral Data Context one, by first introducing the simpler method before exploring other, more complex approaches.

I’d be more than happy to contribute to parts of the documentation where I experienced this feeling of “is there a simpler way to do this first?“. However, I’d like to understand the reasoning behind these documentation decisions, and perhaps who we are targeting with these pages.

Thanks in advance!
Cheers!
reply_text:
Hey <@U0482CK6LCU>! Thanks for this feedback.

In this case, this is was an intentional choice -- in the quickstart, `get_context(...)` will magically create a context based on whatever it is able to introspect from your environment -- that may be an EphemeralDataContext, but if you already have a GX deployment, it will instantiate a context from those configs. The linked guide on creating an EphemeralDataContext is around *explicitly* defining an EDC.

Hey! We are trying to implement an *expect_column_values_to_be_of_type* Expectation. Our data source is in *GCS*, and we only want to load data into our *Snowflake* database that has correct data types. GX runs in a *Cloud Function*.
We are using the *PandasExecutionEngine* on in-memory dataframes, because we are making changes to the header row before further processing.

The problem is that we want to check *SQL* data types, not Python data types. We considered using the SQLAlchemyExecutionEngine, but it seems that we would have to load the data into Snowflake before running GX on it? Alternatively, we believe we could achieve our goal with *RegEx*, but that would be ugly and probably not well performing.

Are we missing something? How can we verify correct Snowflake SQL data types from within a Python Script on data in an in-memory Pandas DF?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04AW6E66AC>! Thanks for reaching out.

If I'm understanding your use-case correctly, I think implementing a Custom Expectation that utilizes some sort of mapping similar to that seen in <https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4165143/easy-convert-betwen-sqlalchemy-column-types-and-python-data-types/57072280#57072280|this SO post> may be the clearest path forward here.

text: Hello, I’m using great expectations with pyspark, but is taking a lot of time to run. Is there a way to speed things up?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04BTF9GK5F>!

You can pass the following:

```concurrency:
  enabled: true```
In your `great_expectations.yml` or as part of your DataContext config. This is still an experimental feature, and may or may not help in every situation.

text: Not sure if it's available somewhere, does anyone know how to add a `row_condition` like col(x).isNotNull() to check for not Null column?

You mean something like this

```import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Check for not null rows

filtered_df = df[not_null_rows]

# Print the filtered DataFrame
print(filtered_df)```

text:
Can Great Expectations support the parameterized expectations of SQL queries, such as the following example:
"select * from TABLE1 rc inner join TABLE2 t2 on t2.coaching_id = rc.coaching_id and t2.learner_id = rc.learner_id
and t2.reviewer_id = rc.reviewer_id and t2.coaching_state in ('CLOSED') and t2.learner_id is not null
and t2.coaching_state_updated_on <= rc.event_ts and (rc.company_id in ${CompanyIds}) and (rc.company_id not in {ExcludedCompanyIds})
and (rc.ingest_ts between {StartHoursBeforeMicro} and {EndHoursBeforeMicro})"
Moreover, can the parameter for the "CompanyIds" be stored in a different file or location?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04HRQ71UEN>! Take a look at <https://github.com/great-expectations/great_expectations/blob/95cf8da8a44f170669ef44a3e0fbe3aa095a597a/contrib/experimental/great_expectations_experimental/expectations/expect_queried_column_values_to_exist_in_second_table_column.py|this Custom Query Expectation>; creating a QueryExpectation in this way allows you to parameterize queries in the way you describe.

Additionally, take a look at our documentation on <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/evaluation_parameter/|Evaluation Parameters>.

text: hi all, i'm using the `get_context()`  function to initialize great expectations inside of my databricks environment. i see all the folders created except for `great_expectations.yml` . is this something i need to create on my own?
reply_text:
Hey <@U04NZV7S57S>! Are you able to share the exact workflow you're utilizing? That will help us to better understand what may be happening here.

Calling `get_context()` alone generally creates an InMemory context, which can be converted to a FileDataContext (including the creation of relevant directories & great_expectations.yml) like this:

```import great_expectations as gx

context = gx.get_context() # I haven't already initialized GX or created a context, so this creates an In-memory context

context.convert_to_file_context() # This initializes the traditional GX structure, including directories & great_expectations.yml```

text: Hi all, I'm using the expectation expect_column_distinct_values_to_contain_set on very large sets (size 10000). The output in the datadocs is showing the list of all the values, therefore the output is not neat to the eye. Is there any way to change the display in the datadocs, for example hide the set values?
reply_text:
Hello! Yes you can.
Use "result_format" to customisation
more information: <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format>
example of using in Checkpoint
```context.run_checkpoint(checkpoint_name="my_checkpoint",
                       validations=[
                           {"batch_request": batch_request},
                       ], 
                       expectation_suite_name="taxi_datasource",
                       result_format = "BOOLEAN_ONLY",
                       )```

text: Hey guys! I am running my checkpoints locally to display validations in Datahub deployed on OpenShift. Its working fine. But running it on Teradata validations wont show up in Datahub. Any hints? There is also no error message whatsoever. Its running the checkpoint fine.
reply_text:
Hi <@U04SJFLN12R> - thanks for the question. There are two factors here:
• GX doesn’t provide full support for Teradata, and we don’t test Teradata functionality at all
• GX doesn’t maintain the Datahub Action, it is maintained by the Datahub team, and we don’t do test this functionality on our end either.
Given these two factors, there is not much we can do to help, but we would recommend reaching out to the team at Acryl/Datahub for additional support.

text: Hi,  I need to work in a very very large Oracle database, but I only need to use data from the last few days. How can I set this in yaml file. I want validations only for the last few days and not the entire table to be read.
reply_text:
Hey <@U04V4CPM3TL> :wave:
Couple of things, firstly, please be advised GX does not offer support for Oracle DBs. It can work in some circumstances and some expectations, but there aren't any guarantees. Secondly, you can filter which data to profile via batch filters.

Hey, <@U04V7JB8HJS> so the problem here is that as far as GX is concerned it's writing to a local file system. It doesn't know there is an S3 bucket behind it. The way to get around it is to configure this step to write to the S3 bucket directly rather than on the mounted file system.

text:
Hi all,
How to make the custom expectation get applied to all the columns in the data for validation. As I have over 100 columns to be validated, It would be laborious to apply expectation to each column specifying one by one through validator. Do you have any functionality or parameter like "include_expectations" for including the expectation to be applied for all the columns while instantiating UserConfigurableProfiler. As I see a parameter which exists to exclude them by passing expectation names to "exclude_expectations" parameter while configuring UserConfigurableProfiler.
reply_text:
Hey <@U050DMFBF3K>! Thanks for reaching out. GX doesn't offer explicit tooling for this functionality; however, it isn't uncommon for users to automate the standard expectation process to iterate through column names and apply their expectations.

Additionally, depending on the logic of the expectation, it may be feasible to create a Custom Table or Custom Query Expectation that applies that logic to each column, rather than a Column-level expectation that must be applied repeatedly.

If you'd like to see functionality like you've described come to GX, please feel free to open a Feature Request on GitHub! :rocket:

Hey <@U050S1NSPV1>! Thanks for reaching out.

To your first question; you should be able to interact with these plots within a notebook to save them. However, this functionality isn't currently supported outside of a notebook.

To you second question, if you're able to provide the complete workflow generating this result, as well as your GX version, we'll be able to better understand what may be happening here.

Hey <@U050S1NSPV1>! Interesting that you're getting that double report; I don't see anything here that should be causing that.

Would you be willing to open a GitHub Issue detailing the behavior you're experiencing with this context? That will help us to better investigate what may be happening here.

text: Could one batch request validates multiple data assets (eg multiple sql tables) together with one expectation suite?
reply_text:
Hey <@U05246K45C4>! Thanks for reaching out.

Typically, a batch request points to a single asset. When utilizing the OnboardingDataAssistant, it is possible to configure multi-batch requests that do what you're describing.

It's also possible to pass a list of Validations to a checkpoint, where each entry in the list is a paring of a batch request point to an asset, and an expectation suite to validate that asset. In this way, it is possible for a single Checkpoint to validate many assets against one or more expectation suites at once.

text:
question : giving regex in data_asset_name while creating checkpoint
description: notebook is showing below code
```my_checkpoint_name = (
    "initial_cp"  # This was populated from your CLI command.
)

yaml_config = f"""
name: {my_checkpoint_name}
config_version: 1.0
class_name: SimpleCheckpoint
run_name_template: "%Y%m%d-%H%M%S-my-run-name-template"
validations:
  - batch_request:
      datasource_name: my_datasource
      data_connector_name: default_inferred_data_connector_name
      data_asset_name: poc/customers/preprocessed/dummy_sample-0
      data_connector_query:
        index: -1
    expectation_suite_name: poc_test_suit_s3
"""
print(yaml_config)```
here data_asset_name  is "poc/customers/preprocessed/dummy_sample-0"
is there a way to provide regex as I want to run this for all the files "dummy_sample-(*)\.csv"
dummy_sample-*0*.csv, dummy_sample-*1*.csv, dummy_sample-*2*.csv and so on....

my datasource look like this
```        default_regex:
          group_names:
            - data_asset_name
          pattern: (.*)\.csv
        bucket: snowflake-stage
        module_name: great_expectations.datasource.data_connector
        class_name: InferredAssetS3DataConnector
        prefix: poc/customers/preprocessed```
reply_text:
Hey <@U053A3WD0HJ>!  Thanks for reaching out.

You can set the `pattern` to match your file names with regex.

For example, something like:

```        default_regex:
          group_names:
            - sample_slice
          pattern: dummy_sample-(.*)\.csv
        bucket: snowflake-stage
        module_name: great_expectations.datasource.data_connector
        class_name: InferredAssetS3DataConnector
        prefix: poc/customers/preprocessed```
should match each of the files you've listed above, allowing you to specify your asset using the `sample_slice` similar to:

```data_connector_query = {
    "batch_filter_parameters": {
        "sample_slice": "0",
    }
}
batch_request = BatchRequest(
    datasource_name="insert_your_datasource_name_here",
    data_connector_name="insert_your_data_connector_name_here",
    data_asset_name="insert_your_data_asset_name_here",
    data_connector_query=data_connector_query)```

Thanks for flagging this, <@U055Z8YTLS1>! As a workaround, can you try the following code instead?

```import great_expectations as gx

print(context)```
We're working to fix `get_context()` so it initializes an empty folder correctly, and in the meantime we'll be updating the docs to reflect the code above instead.

text:
Looking for info on the state of GX as it pertains to two 15.50 features:
• JSONSchema Profiler
• Datahub Integration
Schema profiler behaves incorrectly and is absent from version 16 documentation, and the packages installed for Datahub support roll GX install back to 15.50 (and break my fluent datasources)
reply_text:
Hi <@U055Z8YTLS1>, thanks for checking in on these!

• The JSON Schema Profiler was experimental and not fully developed; we have since removed it from the documentation and would recommend using the <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/expectations/advanced/how_to_create_a_new_expectation_suite_using_rule_based_profilers|Custom Profiler> instead (rule-based). We may support JSON in our future work on Data Assistants and would welcome a feature request in GitHub
• The DataHub integration is owned and maintained by DataHub but according to <https://datahubproject.io/docs/metadata-ingestion/integration_docs/great-expectations/|their docs> they only support V3 (fluent) SQLAlchemy-based data sources. You can reach out to them on their <https://slack.datahubproject.io/|Slack> for guidance

Hello GX team,
I am looking for information/guideline/direction on following on Data Doc :
• Best practice for creating and hosting Data Docs for the production. (S3 or GCS) 
• Best practice for migrating the Data Docs contents to another location.  How to maintain the site index post migration.  Is it docs will get refresh or loss? 
• What is major difference in Build and Update the Data Docs.  Is it the UpdateDataDocsAction will build Data Doc as well.  
• Do we need to run "Build Data Docs" and "Update Data Docs" for every validations . Use case is keep Docs on same site for different applications 
```site_name = "new_site_name"
context.build_data_docs(site_names=site_name
context.open_data_docs(site_name=site_name)```
Appreciate the help on above .
<@UJL2Z9RR9> <@U0588NU8EE5>
reply_text:
Hey <@U05C0U81TB2>! Thanks for reaching out. In the future, please refrain from directly tagging team members.

GX supports hosting docs in a number of ways; <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/setup/configuring_data_docs/host_and_share_data_docs|see this guide for details>.

Data Docs are a series of static html files periodically updated from your validation results -- as long as you bring all of those files over in your migration, and maintain the same directory structure for them, you shouldn't lose any docs.

Building docs rebuilds all of the html files in your docs, as well as generating any new docs from new validation results -- Update data docs should only update docs or build new docs for the actual validation being run.

You don't need to run either at every validation, but if you don't run one of them, your docs won't be updated with the validation results from that validation until you do run one of those actions.

text: hi, I'm trying to apply a <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/conditional_expectations/#scope-and-limitations|Conditional Expectation> of the format
reply_text:
Hey <@U05CFJFFKEF>, thanks for reaching out :tada: The correct syntax doesn't use single quotes: <https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/conditional_expectations/#format-of-row_conditions-values>

In addition, the condition syntax is in Python language and has to be "static", so you have to do the operation before using the conditional expectation, giving the result of evaluation to the expectation. So, in your case, you have to do col("report_name").contains("price") outside the row_condition (maybe adding a column with this result to your dataset), because the function of row_condition is like a filter.
Enjoy GX and feel free to reply with other questions, I'm happy to give support :coffee:

text:
Hey folks,

I'm a newcomer to GX and the GX community. I'm currently exploring the use of Great Expectations for enforcing data quality and validation standards in our datalake.

I'm curious to know if GX can handle scenarios involving data partitioned in a multi-level folder hierarchy on Azure blob store, where each *path containing a file has its unique schema.* In this case, I want to *obtain the schema information* from a separate file and then utilize it to validate and perform various tests on the data file in terms of completeness, *schema checks*, data type etc.

For example:

The folder structure for the *data files* appears as follows:

/_TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=SouthAmerica/country=Mexico/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=India/cuisine.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=Japan/cuisine.parquet_

The folder structure for the *metadata/schema files* appears as follows:

_/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=SouthAmerica/country=Mexico/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=India/schema.parquet_
_/TravelDestinations/continent=Asia/country=Japan/schema.parquet_


Here is an example of how the content of the data and schema files may look like:
reply_text:
Hi <@U05F19E18Q0>, if I had to work with this sample config I would do something like:

```# read a schema file using pandas
italian_schema_df = pd.read_parquet('/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/schema.parquet')

# Extract the names form the schema file (gets Pizza, Pasta, etc. as a series), then convert to a list
italian_schema_items = italian_schema_df['name'].tolist()

# Import Great Expectations
import great_expectations as ge

# Setup the environment
context = gx.get_context()

validator = context.sources.pandas_default.read_parquet('/TravelDestinations/continent=Europe/country=Italy/cuisine.parquet')

# Add an expectation to the validator
validator.expect_table_columns_to_match_set(italian_schema_items)

# Validate your data and visualize the results
checkpoint = context.add_or_update_checkpoint(
    name="my_quickstart_checkpoint",
    validator=validator,
)

checkpoint_result = checkpoint.run()

context.view_validation_result(checkpoint_result)```
This will output a nice html file with a report that shows the results of checking the columns in the cuisine parquet file agains the names in the schema.

Ot course you could iterate over the structure to get this done over all datasets.

I hope it helps!

text: Does the GX v0.17 releases documentation mention about Spark as an in-memory data source. So far I can only see that pandas was mentioned.
reply_text:
Hey <@U05H5UHMNSH>! Thanks for flagging.

The following code should help you from instantiating a datasource through to getting a validator:

```import great_expectations as gx
context = gx.get_context(context_root_dir=<YOUR_ROOT_DIR>)

dataframe_datasource = context.sources.add_or_update_spark(
    name="my_spark_in_memory_datasource",
)

dataframe_asset = dataframe_datasource.add_dataframe_asset(
    name="my_asset",
    dataframe=<YOUR_SPARK_DF>,
)

batch_request = dataframe_asset.build_batch_request()

expectation_suite_name = "insert_your_expectation_suite_name_here"
context.add_or_update_expectation_suite(expectation_suite_name=expectation_suite_name)
validator = context.get_validator(
    batch_request=batch_request,
    expectation_suite_name=expectation_suite_name,
)```
We'll review this gap and address as needed. :bow:
